converting them to simpler categorical values to ease our understanding.¶

In [ ]:
def stop_change(x):
    if x == "non-stop":
        return "zero"
    elif x == "1-stop":
        return "one"
    else:
        return "multiple"

def time_to_period(x):
    hour = x.hour
    if 5 <= hour < 12:
        return "Morning"
    elif 12 <= hour < 17:
        return "Afternoon"
    elif 17 <= hour < 21:
        return "Evening"
    else:
        return "Night"

In [ ]:
def out(df,x):
  q1 = df[x].quantile(0.25)
  q3 = df[x].quantile(0.75)
  iqr = q3 - q1
  lower = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
  upper = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
  outliers = df[(df[x] < lower) | (df[x] > upper)]
  return outliers

The outliers in the price column are present primarily because all identified high-priced flights are in the Business class, have either one or multiple stops, are operated exclusively by Vistara, majority are departing in the morning or evening and some are booked close to the departure date, all of which contribute to significantly higher prices.¶

  • One of the reason might be due to Business class tickets being significantly more expensive than economy class due to additional amenities, more spacious seating, premium services, and higher levels of comfort.
  • Vistara, being the sole airline in the outliers dataset, may have higher pricing strategies for certain routes, especially for business class travelers. This could be due to their target market, service quality, and operational costs.

So we can't exclude the outliers as they are true outliers.

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

best_model = None
best_score = -float('inf')  # Initialize with a very low value

for model_name, (model, param_grid) in models.items():
    print(f"Training {model_name}...")
    random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=model,
                                       param_distributions=param_grid,
                                       n_iter=10,
                                       scoring='r2',
                                       cv=5,
                                       random_state=46)
    random_search.fit(X_feat_train_transformed,y_feat_train)

    # Print the best parameters and score for the current model
    print(f"Best {model_name} parameters: {random_search.best_params_}")
    print(f"Best {model_name} score: {random_search.best_score_}")
    best_models[model_name] = random_search.best_estimator_
    print(best_models)

    # Check if this model is better than the current best one
    if random_search.best_score_ > best_score:
        best_score = random_search.best_score_
        best_model = random_search.best_estimator_

print(f"\nBest Model: {best_model}")
print(f"Best Score: {best_score}")

From the above table, here are a few observations:¶

  • RandomForest, GradientBoosting, and XGBoost models achieve the highest R2 and Adjusted R2 Scores of 0.95.
  • The TheilSen model has an exceptionally high training time (12.761589 seconds), significantly longer than any other model.
  • The KNeighbours model has the highest testing time (1.048659 seconds), which is much longer compared to other models.
  • Ridge has the shortest training time (0.007710 seconds) and very short testing time (0.002706 seconds).
  • XGBoost balances well with a relatively short training time (0.243460 seconds) and testing time (0.021409 seconds).
  • LinearRegression, Ridge, and Lasso models all have identical R2 and Adjusted R2 Scores of 0.91, indicating similar predictive performance.

Conclusion:¶

The best models are the following:¶

  • DecisionTree can be considered the best model with quite the fast prediction time (0.004241 seconds) and with a slight trade-off in the R2 Score (0.94).
  • XGBoost has the best overall performance due to its perfect balance of high R2 Score (0.95) and a bit slow predicition time (0.071349 seconds).

Thus, DecisionTree can be considered the best choice for scenarios where computational efficiency is prioritized and a slight reduction in predictive performance (from 0.95 to 0.94) is acceptable.¶

n = X_test.shape[0]  # number of samples
p = X_test.shape[1]  # number of features

def adj_r2(x):
  return 1 - (1 - x) * (n - 1) / (n - p - 1)

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler
from category_encoders import BinaryEncoder
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from xgboost import XGBRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score

categorical_cols = X.select_dtypes(include="object").columns
numerical_cols = X.select_dtypes(exclude="object").columns

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=47)

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('cat', BinaryEncoder(), categorical_cols),
        ('num', RobustScaler(), numerical_cols)
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'
)
preprocessor

pipeline_XG = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('regressor',  XGBRegressor(max_depth=5, n_estimators=74, learning_rate=0.3))
])

pipeline_XG.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_XG = pipeline_XG.predict(X_test)

mae_score_XG = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_XG)
mse_score_XG = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_XG)
rmse_score_XG = np.sqrt(mse_score_XG)
r2_score_XG = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_XG)
adj_r2_score_XG = adj_r2(r2_score_XG)

print("Mean Absolute Error:", round(mae_score_XG,2))
print("Mean Squared Error:", round(mse_score_XG,2))
print("Root Mean Squared Error:", round(rmse_score_XG,2))
print("R2 Score:", round(r2_score_XG,2))
print("Adjusted R2 Score:", round(adj_r2_score_XG,2))



     






















    
    






Mean Absolute Error: 2947.7
Mean Squared Error: 25596111.48
Root Mean Squared Error: 5059.26
R2 Score: 0.95
Adjusted R2 Score: 0.95
